If Ralph R. Eltse had managed to sway an additional 2.5% of the total vote from his opponent, what would the outcome of the election in California 7 have been?
answer: If Ralph R. Eltse had gained 2.5 percentage points from his opponent, his vote share would have become 50.2% (47.7% + 2.5%), while John H. Tolan's would have dropped to 49.8% (52.3% - 2.5%). As a result, Ralph R. Eltse would have won the re-election instead of losing.

question: Based on the outcomes, is there a discernible correlation between an incumbent's party and their likelihood of facing an opponent?
answer: Based on this data, there is no discernible correlation. Of the five Republican incumbents, two ran unopposed (40%). Of the four Democratic incumbents (including the one who retired), two were re-elected unopposed (50%). The rates are very similar, suggesting party affiliation was not a strong predictor of facing an opponent in this dataset.

Which district's election result is a significant outlier in terms of margin of victory when compared to the other contested race?
answer: The election in California 19 is a significant outlier. The winner, Sam L. Collins, achieved a victory margin of 77.6 percentage points (88.8% vs 11.2%). This is exceptionally high compared to the only other contested race, California 7, which was decided by a narrow margin of just 4.6 percentage points (52.3% vs 47.7%).
